# Launch Pad вЂ” Cursor Rules

## What This Project Is

Launch Pad is a unified developer cockpit that manages GitHub, Vercel, Supabase, and Claude/Anthropic from one dark-mode UI. It eliminates backend friction for builders who hate terminals. Users authenticate once per service, and the app handles tokens, permissions, env vars, and agent orchestration.

## The Stack

- **Framework:** Next.js 15 with App Router
- **Language:** TypeScript
- **Styling:** Tailwind CSS with custom theme (see tailwind.config.js)
- **Auth:** Clerk вЂ” `middleware.ts` gates `/app`; marketing routes public. No custom session cookies.
- **Billing (coming):** Stripe via Clerk billing integration
- **Database (coming):** Supabase for user vault, agent memories, sessions
- **APIs:** GitHub REST, Vercel REST, Supabase PostgREST, Anthropic Messages API

## Architecture Rules

- No custom backend. Use Next.js API routes only.
- All API keys entered by the user are stored client-side in localStorage (will migrate to encrypted Supabase Vault when auth is added).
- API calls to third-party services (GitHub, Vercel, Supabase, Anthropic) happen client-side in the prototype. When splitting into production, move them to API routes to keep secrets server-side.
- Never write custom auth middleware. Clerk handles everything.
- The `vault` object in state holds all user tokens. Check `vault.github`, `vault.vercel`, `vault.supabase_url`, `vault.supabase_anon`, `vault.supabase_service`, `vault.anthropic`.

## Design System

- **Background:** #09090b
- **Card background:** rgba(255,255,255,0.02) with 1px border rgba(255,255,255,0.06)
- **Typography:** DM Sans for UI, JetBrains Mono for code/data
- **Service colors:**
  - GitHub: #8b6cf6 (purple)
  - Vercel: #ffffff (white)
  - Supabase: #3ecf8e (green)
  - Claude: #d97750 (amber)
- **Primary action:** #00e676 (green) вЂ” buttons, CTAs, success states
- **Danger:** #ff5252
- **Warning:** #ffd740
- **Info:** #40c4ff
- **Design vibe:** Robinhood meets Bloomberg terminal. Dark, premium, bright accent buttons. Never generic. No Inter, no purple-on-white gradients, no AI slop.

